REMINDER: JH and High school students

ALL 7th and 9th graders are required to get physicals this year. 7th graders also need to bring a copy of their updated immunizations (yes, you have to get shots!)

All returning 10th-12th graders that have physicals on file will not have to get new ones this year. If you did not turn one in last year you will need one if you plan on playing sports.

ALL high school students will need to fill out a new NSAA form for the 2020-21 school year (if you are planning on being in sports/band/vocal). Those are included in your packet, so make sure you fill them out!

Any questions, please call the office! 962-5458
~Mrs. Deisley

*******************************UPDATE***********************************
Congratulations to the following Arapahoe art students for winning awards at the McCook Community College virtual art show.

3-Dimensional-Judges Choice Award
Tanner Deisley- American Flag made of wood

Printmaking- Judges Choice Award
Lauren Bahe- John Lennon- Linoleum reduction prints. Lauren finished these at home during the first week of quarantine.

Drawing- Judges Choice Award
Butterflies- White colored pencil on black paper
***************************************************************************

McCook Community College is displaying a Virtual High School Art School Show, highlighting over 450 pieces of art from area high school students.

post_text:
March 11, 2020



Dear Families,

At the Girl‚Äôs State Basketball tournament this past week, a spectator attended the games who tested positive for (COVID-19). After speaking with the Southwest Nebraska Health Department regarding this event, I was informed that the risk to our girls and coaches was very low and there are no other steps we need to take at this time. As an added measure of caution, I have requested the coaches and girls to take their temperature daily and not attend school if their temperature is over 99.5 degrees. They also need to inform the district immediately so we can consult with the Health Department to see if any additional steps will be needed.

Be clear that the risk of exposure is very low and I will keep you informed if there are any changes.

Sincerely,

Dr. George Griffith

post_text:
Cord and Reilley's National History Day Documentary

Thesis: With tensions between the USSR and the United States boiling up, the launch of Sputnik 1 launched the world into the Space Race. Sputnik 1 was the first man-made satellite to break the barrier of space and was one of the most important first steps in space exploration. Sputnik 1 not only increased tensions during an already hot Cold War but it also changed the American attitude on education, foreign policy, and space exploration.

post_text:
Tuesday, some of our Warriors attended the #strivwintersummit at Midland University hosted by Striv.

They started the morning hearing from Joseph Allen, a golden buzzer winner on America's Got Talent. He spoke to the kids about his inspiring story and how he worked hard to find his creative talent and continues to push himself in chasing his goals.

They then spent the rest of the morning learning about digital marketing and creating your own brand. They learned how to better use social media to share their story. They also learned new and awesome social media strategies, how to write effective copy, and post engaging content.

We are looking forward to more opportunities like this as we dive deeper into our Striv community!

post_text: Maggie Weatherwax was recognized for Service and Leadership at the Lexington Speech Tournament on January 11th. Maggie has been involved in the Speech community for six (6) years, starting as a junior high competitor, and continuing to help develop the junior high team every year since. A senior at Arapahoe High School, Maggie has competed in entertainment, humorous, duet, and OID. She has competed in every conference and district meet offered, and is an encourager to her teammates. She has mastered the art of serving through her consistent leadership in all situations. She finds great stories, tells great stories, and has become fluent in script-cutting and writing. Maggie has used her gifts in language to speak at the state Capitol, and perform three years at the national level in National History Day. Thank you, Maggie.
